1. Bayesian networks and naïve Bayes classifiers.

a) Given a training dataset including 10 observations and a Bayesian network indicating the relationships between 3 features (i.e. Income, Student and Credit Rate) and the class attribute (i.e. Buy Computer), please create the conditional probability tables by hand.

P(Income=High|Buy=Yes) = 5/12 = 0.42

P(Income=Low|Buy=Yes) = 7/12 = 0.58

P(Income=High|Buy=No) = 7/18 = 0.39

P(Income=Low|Buy=No) = 11/18 = 0.61

P(Student=TRUE|Buy=Yes) = 6/12 = 0.5

P(Student=FALSE|Buy=Yes) = 6/12 = 0.5

P(Student=TRUE|Buy=No) = 12/18 = 0.67

P(Student=FALSE|Buy=No) = 6/18 = 0.33

P(Credit=Fair|Income=High,Student=TRUE,Buy=Yes) = 1/2 = 0.5

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=High,Student=TRUE,Buy=Yes) = 1/2 = 0.5

P(Credit=Fair|Income=High,Student=TRUE,Buy=No) = 3/4 = 0.75

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=High,Student=TRUE,Buy=No) = 1/4 = 0.25

P(Credit=Fair|Income=Low,Student=TRUE,Buy=Yes) = 2/4 = 0.5

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=Low,Student=TRUE,Buy=Yes) = 2/4 = 0.5

P(Credit=Fair|Income=Low,Student=TRUE,Buy=No) = 6/8 = 0.75

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=Low,Student=TRUE,Buy=No) = 2/8 = 0.75

P(Credit=Fair|Income=High,Student=FALSE,Buy=Yes) = 1/3 = 0.33

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=High,Student=FALSE,Buy=Yes) = 2/3 = 0.67

P(Credit=Fair|Income=High,Student=FALSE,Buy=No) = 1/3 = 0.33

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=High,Student=FALSE,Buy=No) = 2/3 = 0.67

P(Credit=Fair|Income=Low,Student=FALSE,Buy=Yes) = 1/3 = 0.33

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=Low,Student=FALSE,Buy=Yes) = 2/3 = 0.67

P(Credit=Fair|Income=Low,Student=FALSE,Buy=No) = 2/3 = 0.67

P(Credit=Excellent|Income=Low,Student=FALSE,Buy=No) = 1/3 = 0.33

b) Make predictions for 2 testing observations by using a Bayesian network classifier.

Observation 1

P(Buy=Yes,Income=Low,Student=True,Credit=Excellent)

= P(Credit=Excellent | Income=Low, Student=True, Buy=Yes) x P(Student=True | Buy=Yes) x P(Income=Low | Buy=Yes) x P(Buy=Yes)

= 0.5 * 0.5 * 0.58 * 0.4 = 0.058

Observation 2

P(Buy=Yes, Income=High, Student=True, Credit=Fair)

= P(Credit=Fair | Income=Low, Student=True, Buy=Yes) x P(Student=True | Buy=Yes) x P(Income=High | Buy=Yes) x P(Buy=Yes)

= 0.5 * 0.5 * 0.42 * 0.4 = 0.042

c) Based on the conditional independence assumption between features, please create the conditional probability tables by hand.

P(Income=High|Buy=Yes) = 5/12 = 0.42

P(Income=Low|Buy=Yes) = 7/12 = 0.58

P(Income=High|Buy=No) = 7/18 = 0.39

P(Income=Low|Buy=No) = 11/18 = 0.61

P(Student=TRUE|Buy=Yes) = 6/12 = 0.5

P(Student=FALSE|Buy=Yes) = 6/12 = 0.5

P(Student=TRUE|Buy=No) = 12/18 = 0.67

P(Student=FALSE|Buy=No) = 6/18 = 0.33

P(Credit=Fair|Buy=Yes) = 5/12 = 0.42

P(Credit=Excellent|Buy=Yes) = 7/12 = 0.58

P(Credit=Fair|Buy=No) = 12/18 = 0.67

P(Credit=Excellent|Buy=No) = 6/18 = 0.33

d) Make predictions for 2 testing observations by using a naïve Bayes classifier.

Observation 1

P(Buy=Yes,Income=Low,Student=True,Credit=Excellent) = P(Credit=Excellent | Buy=Yes) x P(Student=True | Buy=Yes) x P(Income=Low | Buy=Yes) x P(Buy=Yes)

= 0.58 * 0.5 * 0.58 * 0.4 = 0.067

P(Buy=No,Income=Low,Student=True,Credit=Excellent)

= P(Credit=Excellent | Buy=No) x P(Student=True | Buy=No) x P(Income=Low | Buy=No) x P(Buy=No)

= 0.33 * 0.67 * 0.61 * 0.6 = 0.081

Observation 1 Prediction => Buy = No

Observation 2

P(Buy=Yes, Income=High, Student=True, Credit=Fair)

= P(Credit=Fair | Buy=Yes) x P(Student=True | Buy=Yes) x P(Income=High | Buy=Yes) x P(Buy=Yes)

= 0.42 * 0.5 * 0.42 * 0.4 = 0.035

P(Buy=No, Income=High, Student=True, Credit=Fair)

= P(Credit=Fair | Buy=No) x P(Student=True | Buy=No) x P(Income=High | Buy=No) x P(Buy=No)

= 0.67 * 0.67 * 0.39 * 0.6 = 0.105

Observation 2 Prediction => Buy = No

For both Observations, using naïve Bayes classifier we predict No.

2. Predicting room occupancy by using decision tree and random forests classification algorithms.

(a) Load the room occupancy training and testing datasets that are also used for the 1st coursework. Train a decision tree classifier and evaluate the predictive performance by reporting the classification accuracy obtained on the testing dataset.

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(tree)

training_set <- read.table('Room_Occupancy_Training_set.txt', header=TRUE, sep = ',')
testing_set <- read.table('Room_Occupancy_Testing_set.txt', header=TRUE, sep = ',')

training_set$Occupancy <- as.factor(training_set$Occupancy)
testing_set$Occupancy <- as.factor(testing_set$Occupancy)

tree.training_set <- tree(Occupancy ~ Temperature+Humidity+Light+CO2+HumidityRatio, training_set)

occupancy.testing_set <- testing_set$Occupancy

tree.testing_set.pred <- predict(tree.training_set, testing_set, type="class")

mean(tree.testing_set.pred == occupancy.testing_set)
## [1] 0.7966667
table(tree.testing_set.pred, occupancy.testing_set)
##                      occupancy.testing_set
## tree.testing_set.pred   0   1
##                     0 195  16
##                     1  45  44

The classification accuracy is 79.7%. We can see 61 rooms in total were classified inaccurately. 45 rooms that were not occupied were incorrectly classified as occupied and 16 occupied rooms were incorrectly classified as unoccupied.

(b) Output and analyse the tree learned by the decision tree algorithm, i.e. plot the tree structure and make a discussion about it.

plot(tree.training_set)
text(tree.training_set,pretty=0)

A few key things to note are that if the light is less than 162.8, there is 0% chance of the room being occupied. We can see if the temperature is less than 22.21 and light is less greater than 162.8, the room will be occupied. Humidity looks like the least important factor when compared to Light and Temperature.

5. PCA and K-Means Clustering

In this problem, you will generate simulated data, and then perform PCA and K-means clustering on the data.

(a) Generate a simulated data set with 20 observations in each of three classes (i.e. 60 observations total), and 50 variables.

Hint: There are a number of functions in R that you can use to generate data. One example is the rnorm() function; runif() is another option. Be sure to add a mean shift to the observations in each class so that there are three distinct classes.

set.seed(1)
class1 <- matrix(rnorm(20*50, mean = 5), ncol = 50)
class2 <- matrix(rnorm(20*50,  mean = 10), ncol = 50)
class3 <- matrix(rnorm(20*50, mean = 20), ncol = 50)

data <- cbind(rbind(class1, class2, class3),class = as.factor(c( rep(1,20), rep(2,20), rep(3,20) )))

data <- data.frame(data)

dim(data)
## [1] 60 51

(b) Perform PCA on the 60 observations and plot the first two principal components’ eigenvector. Use a different color to indicate the observations in each of the three classes. If the three classes appear separated in this plot, then continue on to part (c). If not, then return to part (a) and modify the simulation so that there is greater separation between the three classes. Do not continue to part (c) until the three classes show at least some separation in the first two principal component eigenvectors.

pca = prcomp(data, scale=FALSE)

plot(pca$x[,1:2], col = c(rep(1, 20), rep(2, 20), rep(3, 20)))

The three classes are seperate as displayed in the graph.

(c) Perform K-means clustering of the observations with K = 3. How well do the clusters that you obtained in K-means clustering compare to the true class labels? Hint: You can use the table() function in R to compare the true class labels to the class labels obtained by clustering. Be careful how you interpret the results: K-means clustering will arbitrarily number the clusters, so you cannot simply check whether the true class labels and clustering labels are the same.

set.seed(1)
km = kmeans(data,3,nstart= 20)

table(km$cluster,c(rep(1, 20), rep(2, 20), rep(3, 20)),dnn=c("Clusters","Class Labels"))
##         Class Labels
## Clusters  1  2  3
##        1  0  0 20

##        3  0 20  0

Kmeans splits the number of rows into even clusters. Cluster 1,2 and 3 all have 20 observations.

km_pca <- kmeans(pca$x[,1:2],3, nstart=20)

table(km_pca$cluster,c(rep(1, 20), rep(2, 20), rep(3, 20)),dnn=c("Clusters","Class Labels"))
##         Class Labels
## Clusters  1  2  3
##        1  0  0 20
##        2 20  0  0
##        3  0 20  0

We get the same results as the first instance of clustering where the observations are clustered perfectly.

(g) Using the scale() function, perform K-means clustering with K = 3 on the data after scaling each variable to have standard deviation one. How do these results compare to the true class labels? Will the scaling affect the clustering?

scaled_data = scale(data)
km = kmeans(scaled_data, 3, nstart=20)
table(km$cluster,c(rep(1, 20), rep(2, 20), rep(3, 20)),dnn=c("Clusters","Class Labels"))
##         Class Labels
## Clusters  1  2  3
##        1 20  0  0
##        2  0  0 20
##        3  0 20  0

Scaling the data perfectly splits the Class labels into the 3 clusters, similar to the kmeans without scaling. It is sometimes possible that scaling will affect the clustering as it changes the relationship/distance between the data points as it is not the same raw data anymore.
